# FixMySpine Project Rules

## Language & Spelling

**IMPORTANT: This project uses Australian English exclusively for all user-facing content.**

### Australian English Spelling Standards

Always use Australian English spelling conventions:

- **-ise endings**: Use `-ise` not `-ize`
  - ✅ `specialise`, `personalise`, `recognise`, `organise`, `analyse`, `optimise`, `minimise`, `customise`
  - ❌ `specialize`, `personalize`, `recognize`, `organize`, `analyze`, optimize`, `minimize`, `customize`

- **-our endings**: Use `-our` not `-or`
  - ✅ `colour`, `favour`, `behaviour`, `honour`, `labour`, `neighbour`
  - ❌ `color`, `favor`, `behavior`, `honor`, `labor`, `neighbor`

- **-re endings**: Use `-re` not `-er`
  - ✅ `centre`, `theatre`, `metre`, `litre`, `fibre`
  - ❌ `center`, `theater`, `meter`, `liter`, `fiber`

- **-ce endings**: Use `-ce` not `-se` for nouns
  - ✅ `licence` (noun), `practise` (verb), `defence`, `offence`
  - ❌ `license` (noun), `practice` (verb), `defense`, `offense`

- **-tion endings**: Use `-sion` where appropriate
  - ✅ `organisation`, `authorisation`, `realisation`, `mobilisation`
  - ❌ `organization`, `authorization`, `realization`, `mobilization`

- **Double L**: Use double consonants
  - ✅ `travelled`, `travelling`, `traveller`, `cancelled`, `labelled`, `modelled`
  - ❌ `traveled`, `traveling`, `traveler`, `canceled`, `labeled`, `modeled`

- **Other Australian preferences**:
  - ✅ `grey`, `jewellery`, `catalogue`, `dialogue`, `fulfil`, `enrol`, `skilful`
  - ❌ `gray`, `jewelry`, `catalog`, `dialog`, `fulfill`, `enroll`, `skillful`

### Exceptions (American English Allowed)

The following technical contexts may retain American English spelling:

1. **Code & Technical Terms**:
   - CSS class names (e.g., `text-center`, `items-center`) - Tailwind CSS standard
   - JavaScript functions (e.g., `initialize`, `normalize`) - Programming conventions
   - npm package names and dependencies
   - Database column names and code identifiers

2. **Third-Party Standards**:
   - Schema.org markup (e.g., `"@type": "Organization"`)
   - API specifications
   - Library/framework documentation

3. **File Types**:
   - Configuration files (package.json, etc.)
   - Technical documentation that follows international standards

### Where to Apply Australian English

✅ **Always use Australian English in:**
- All EJS view templates (user-facing content)
- Blog posts and articles
- Marketing copy and email templates
- Legal documents (Terms, Privacy Policy)
- User interface text and labels
- Form field labels and help text
- Error messages and notifications
- Meta descriptions and SEO content
- Documentation intended for users/practitioners
- Seed data descriptions
- Comments in view files

## Project Context

FixMySpine is an Australian healthcare directory connecting patients with allied health professionals across Australia. The site must reflect Australian language, culture, and professional standards throughout.

### Target Audience
- Primary: Australian patients seeking healthcare
- Secondary: Australian healthcare practitioners
- Geographic focus: Australia-wide

### Tone & Voice
- Professional yet approachable
- Clear and trustworthy
- Australian terminology for healthcare and business

## Development Standards

### Code Style
- Use meaningful variable and function names
- Write clear comments for complex logic
- Follow existing patterns in the codebase

### Accessibility
- Ensure all interactive elements are keyboard accessible
- Provide appropriate ARIA labels
- Maintain good colour contrast ratios
- Test with screen readers where applicable

### SEO Requirements
- Include proper meta tags on all public pages
- Use semantic HTML structure
- Implement structured data (Schema.org)
- Optimise for Australian search terms

## Testing Requirements

- Test all user-facing features thoroughly
- Verify mobile responsiveness
- Check cross-browser compatibility
- Validate forms with edge cases
- Test with Australian postcodes and addresses

## Important Notes

- Always use Australian date formats (DD/MM/YYYY)
- Use Australian currency (AUD) with proper formatting
- Reference Australian business regulations and standards
- Use metric measurements (kilometres, kilograms, etc.)
- Australian phone number formats: (0X) XXXX XXXX or 04XX XXX XXX
- Australian postcodes: 4 digits (XXXX)

